author: rdklein

description.text: Just having some fun with fractal patterns. SO COOL!

The regular calibration cubes may not be the best thing to calibrate a printer. Edges and particularly the bottoms can be distorted. If you measure the overall size this can yield a slightly inaccurate measure of scale.
This thing has lines and diamonds on both horizontal and vertical faces at 25mm spacing. I have uploaded 3 variants of this thing. The complete corner will give a little bit more information but the choice is yours. I have other test patterns here -
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:23965

Ideally you should slice with the layer height being a factor of the Z distance you are going to measure.
For example .4mm slices requires 62.5 layers to build 25mm in height.
But 50 mm is 125 full layers.
.25mm should be good except the .4mm lines of the vertical faces might slice strangely.
However there should be enough marks visible to get your calipers into.

The mount can be downloaded in two formats.  The first file is one solid object that can be printed using dissolvable support.  The second  file is three parts of the mount that can be glued together after printing with minimal breakaway support.

You can customize the circular cutout radius' to fit your specific razor(s) / brush. Both versions are in the scad file.

comments.text: this is more of a general question. I see the word parametric on a lot of 3D models on here but I really don't understand what context the word is being used in. Is it just a buzz word being used to sound interesting or is there an actual reason for the word usage? I have been 3d modeling for 15 years but i'm new to 3d printing. For example with this model its a polygon-style shell, but I also see the word parametric used on models that are very curvy and flowing. any help?
comments.author: NoahHornberger

comments.text:
Parametric models are those which take parameters. As you may well know, you can design models which are of a fixed size and do not change. It is also possible to design models in a more programatic fashion (eg., a small program which generates an STL file). OpenSCAD is an example of a language which lets you do this.
The result is a model like this pot, where you can size it to your needs. Thingiverse makes this process possible to do in the web browser (as opposed to using the OpenSCAD program). I personally prefer to make my models parameterized because it allows me to design first, then check/update the important parameters before manufacturing. If the fit isn't right, I can make a minute adjustment and reprint very easily.
thank you, now i get it!
comments.author: buckyball

comments.text: it's water resistent?
comments.author: Simmons

comments.text:
If you are asking whether or not it holds water after printing, that depends on the printer you use. I don't trust FDM printers to make a watertight container, but the objects can be made water tight with post processing. The one I printed is tight enough to keep the dirt moist, but any pooling water comes out.
If you use ABS as your material, then Weld-On #4 can be brushed on the inner or outer surface to smooth it (which also happens to create a solid shell by filling any holes).
In the picture attached to this thing, I used PLA which is a bit more resistant to solvents. I was thinking about painting liquid rubber on the bottom, but in the end decided to just use a saucer. The plant I put in it doesn't like too much water anyways.
